Sample code snippet. Notice that you can provide a toggle to switch between coding languages - this is referred to as a ‚Äòtabset‚Äô in quarto. It is good practice to try and convert your R code to python, and vice-versa to demonstrate coding proficiency. For example, let‚Äôs showcase a function for calculating NDVI in R and Python.

RPython


calc_ndvi &lt;- function(nir, red){
  ndvi &lt;- (nir-red)/(nir+red)
  return(ndvi)
}
(Assuming nir and red are terra rast objects)


def calc_ndvi(nir, red): 
  ndvi = (nir - red)/(nir + red)
  return(ndvi)
(Assuming nir and red are numpy arrays)

You can also provide a frame linking to external websites. For example, here is a Google Earth Engine application I developed - which I embedded in this webpage using the code below:


